;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://w=
ww.vox.com/2016/4/12/11407982/paul-ryan-donald-trump-moderate">Paul Ryan is=
n't a moderate alternative to Donald Trump. He's not a moderate
 at all.</a></span></b><span style=3D"font-size:14.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><b><span style=3D"font-size:14.0pt;font-family:&quot=
;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">VOX // DYLAN MATTHEWS &nbsp;<o:p>=
</o:p></span></b></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Paul Ryan is not officially running =
for president, but he's sure<span style=3D"color:#1F497D">
<a href=3D"http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/11/us/politics/paul-ryan-a-mirage=
-candidate-wages-a-parallel-campaign.html">
acting like a presidential candidate</a></span>. He's hoping he can frame h=
imself as a unifying figure in the Republican race for the nomination, a no=
n-fringe Republican who isn't an unpredictable demagogue like Donald Trump,=
 an ideological extremist like Ted
 Cruz, or a repeated failure as a candidate like John Kasich.<o:p></o:p></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">&quot;The youthful, widely-respected=
 House Speaker combines Ted Cruz&#8217;s intellectual conservatism with Joh=
n Kasich&#8217;s moderate congressional track record, a touch of a reformis=
t
 impulse, plus the added bonus of not being Donald Trump,&quot; <span style=
=3D"color:#1F497D">
<a href=3D"http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/04/paul-ryan-president-conve=
ntion">Vanity Fair's Tina Nguyen</a>
</span>summarizes.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">This idea of Ryan as a serious adult=
 with a &quot;moderate congressional track record&quot; is a tempting one, =
but let's not fool ourselves. Ryan talks a good game about caring
 about poverty and rejecting the &quot;makers versus takers&quot; frame of =
many conservatives. But in his time as a national figure, he's been a consi=
stent advocate of aggressive cuts to the social safety net and to Social Se=
curity and Medicare, and for tax reforms at
 least as regressive as those envisioned by Cruz and Trump.<o:p></o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Paul Ryan is many things. But he is =
no moderate.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" align=3D"center" style=3D"text-align:center"><span s=
tyle=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;seri=
f&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin-bottom:12.0pt"><b><span style=3D"fon=
t-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Pa=
ul Ryan is coming for your Social Security and Medicare<o:p></o:p></span></=
b></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Ryan first came to public prominence=
 in 2005, as one of the most vocal proponents of privatizing Social Securit=
y in the House GOP. His specific plan,
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/bdqu=
ery/z?d109:h.r.01776:">the Social Security Personal Savings Guarantee and P=
rosperity Act</a></span>, was the most radical floated during that period. =
It would have allowed workers to
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"https://www.washingtonpost.com/blo=
gs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/08/11/paul-ryans-non-budget-policy-record-in-one-post=
/">redirect more than half</a>
</span>of their 12.4 percent payroll tax contribution to Social Security in=
to a private account, with poorer workers being able to redirect more.<o:p>=
</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">The Center on Budget and Policy Prio=
rities estimated that the plan would
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.cbpp.org/research/priva=
te-accounts-would-substantially-increase-federal-debt-and-interest-payments=
?fa=3Dview&amp;id=3D497#_ftn2">increase the debt by 93.7 percent of GDP</a>
</span>&#8212; a more than doubling &#8212; by 2050. The problem is that by=
 radically reducing payroll tax revenue, the plan would require a huge, ong=
oing infusion of revenue from income taxes and other sources. Specifically,=
 it'd require an
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.cbpp.org/research/the-r=
yan-sununu-social-security-plan?fa=3Dview&amp;id=3D222">ongoing tax increas=
e</a>
</span>of 1.5 percent of GDP, or about $280 billion a year. The revenue sho=
rtfall the plan would create would more than double the Social Security sho=
rtfall at the time, thereby worsening the very problem the proposal was int=
ended to solve.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Whatever Ryan's Social Security plan=
 was, it wasn't moderate. In fact, the Bush administration rejected it in a
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1104=
96995612018199">leaked memo</a></span>. While Bush staffer Peter Wehner did=
 not name Ryan, he was clearly talking about the bill, calling it &quot;irr=
esponsible.&quot;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Ryan doesn't talk about his Social S=
ecurity proposals much anymore, but they made their way into his first few =
budget plans. His initial &quot;<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://web.archive.org/web/20080528060215/http:/americanroadmap.org/">Roadma=
p
 for America's Future</a></span>&quot; in 2008 included a plan to allow 5.1=
 percent of the 12.4 percent in Social Security payroll taxes to go to priv=
ate accounts. The plan would've also increased the retirement age and adopt=
ed &quot;<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.cbpp.org/resea=
rch/progressive-price-indexing-would-significantly-cut-social-security-bene=
fits-for-many">progressive
 price indexing</a></span>,&quot; a scheme for cutting benefits by having m=
iddle-class and upper-income workers' benefits rise with inflation rather t=
han with wage growth. The private accounts idea was retained in his
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"https://web.archive.org/web/201002=
01041359/http:/www.roadmap.republicans.budget.house.gov/Plan/#retirementsec=
urity">2010 proposal</a>
</span>but<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"> <a href=3D"http://budget.house.gov=
/uploadedfiles/pathtoprosperityfy2012.pdf">
abandoned in 2011</a></span>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Ryan's Medicare reform proposals are=
 better-known. The 2008 and 2010 budget proposals fully privatized the prog=
ram, replacing it for workers under 55 with a &quot;<span style=3D"color:#1=
F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB100014240527487038089045750=
25080017959478">Medicare
 payment</a></span>&quot; to be used to purchase private insurance. This is=
 a major cut, as the value of the voucher would be less than expected spend=
ing on Medicare per beneficiary; what's more, Medicare pays doctors less th=
an private health insurers, so even a
 voucher of equal value would <span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http=
://voices.washingtonpost.com/ezra-klein/2010/02/rep_paul_ryans_daring_budge=
t_p.html">effectively buy less care for seniors</a></span>.<o:p></o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Like the Social Security plan, the M=
edicare proposal has moderated with time. After collaborating on a
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.politico.com/story/2011=
/12/ryan-wyden-back-a-new-medicare-option-070459">compromise version</a>
</span>with Sen. Ron Wyden (D-OR), Ryan's later budgets let seniors choose =
traditional Medicare if they preferred that to buying private insurance.<o:=
p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Taken all together, is this plan mor=
e &quot;moderate&quot; than those of Donald Trump or Ted Cruz? Not at all. =
Trump has been vocal in arguing against any cuts to Social Security
 or Medicare, placing him well to the left of Ryan, one of Washington's big=
gest supporters of Social Security and Medicare cuts, on the issue. Cruz su=
pports
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.npr.org/2016/03/12/4701=
30961/fact-check-republican-candidates-on-keeping-or-changing-social-securi=
ty">personal accounts</a>,
<a href=3D"http://www.cnbc.com/2015/10/26/social-security-why-dont-the-cand=
idates-get-it-commentary.html">
progressive price indexing</a></span>, and gradually increasing the retirem=
ent age, as well as
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.ontheissues.org/Archive=
/2012_AARP_Ted_Cruz.htm">Ryan-esque privatization of Medicare</a></span>, p=
utting him basically in line with Ryan on entitlement issues.<o:p></o:p></s=
pan></p>
