se yet</a></span>, even though the 2015 tax deal provided a perfect opportu=
nity to do so. While that deal finally
 made the EITC expansions in the 2009 stimulus package permanent, that was =
a change that Ryan
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.vox.com/2014/12/2/73203=
63/eitc-child-credit-ryan">resisted for years</a>.<o:p></o:p></span></span>=
</p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;color:#1F497D"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Outside of the EITC, Ryan's poverty =
plan is basically the same as his early budgets. He wants to<span style=3D"=
color:#1F497D">
<a href=3D"http://www.vox.com/cards/paul-ryan-poverty/what-is-paul-ryans-op=
portunity-grant-program">
block-grant Medicaid and SNAP</a></span>. He wants to <span style=3D"color:=
#1F497D">
<a href=3D"http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/07/paul-ryans-paternal=
istic-poverty-plan.html">force poor families to develop a &quot;contract&qu=
ot; with the government</a>
</span>or a nonprofit to get themselves out of poverty, a deeply condescend=
ing and paternalistic approach that fails to address both weak labor market=
s for the poor and the fact that the social services agencies that'd be adm=
inistering these kinds of contracts
 would see a lot less funding with the discretionary cuts Ryan favors.<span=
 style=3D"color:#1F497D"><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;color:#1F497D"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Is this agenda more moderate than Tr=
ump or Cruz? Not really. Trump basically shares Ryan's agenda for the poor,=
 calling for
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"https://www.donaldjtrump.com/posit=
ions/healthcare-reform">block-granting Medicaid</a>
</span>and <span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.ibtimes.com/=
donald-trump-right-about-food-stamps-republican-presidential-candidate-quot=
es-wrong-2195441">attacking the food stamps program</a></span>. Same with
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.usnews.com/opinion/blog=
s/pat-garofalo/2013/06/12/house-and-senate-farm-bills-cut-food-stamps">Cruz=
</a></span>. If anything, the two have been much less detailed than Ryan in=
 explaining how they plan to increase
 poverty in America.<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><br>
<br>
</span><b>Ryan's tax cuts are about as massive as Trump's<o:p></o:p></b></s=
pan></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">Ryan has always included massive tax=
 cut proposals in his budgets. Traditionally, the cornerstone of the plans =
is the replacement of the current bracket structure with
 just two rates: 10 percent up to $50,000 ($100,000 for couples), and 25 pe=
rcent above that point.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">His initial plan would've replaced t=
he corporate income tax with an 8.5 percent value-added tax, subjected all =
health insurance to income and payroll taxation, and ended
 all taxation of investment income. It would've let taxpayers choose betwee=
n the current individual tax system and a new one with 10 and 25 percent ra=
tes and no itemized deductions or credits. The
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://webcache.googleusercontent.=
com/search?q=3Dcache:lOfqySSmwDwJ:www.taxpolicycenter.org/numbers/displayat=
ab.cfm%3FDocid%3D2687&#43;&amp;cd=3D4&amp;hl=3Den&amp;ct=3Dclnk&amp;gl=3Dus=
">Tax Policy Center</a>
</span>estimated that it would increase taxes for people making $20,000 to =
$200,000 but give millionaires an average tax cut of more than $500,000. It=
 would've led to a
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.theatlantic.com/busines=
s/archive/2010/03/how-paul-ryan-would-transform-the-us-tax-system/37420/">h=
uge reduction in revenue</a></span>, leading to a<span style=3D"color:#1F49=
7D">
<a href=3D"http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/taxvox/defense-congressman-paul-r=
yan">$4 trillion shortfall over 10 years</a>.<br>
<br>
</span>Ryan's plan hasn't gotten much better in <span style=3D"color:#1F497=
D"><a href=3D"http://www.vox.com/cards/paul-ryan-budget/what-does-paul-ryan=
s-budget-do-with-taxes">later iterations</a></span>. He abandoned the choic=
e-of-plans aspect and the VAT idea.
 He went silent on abandoning taxation of all investment income. Instead, h=
e'd cut the corporate income tax rate to 25 percent and exclude foreign pro=
fits, retain the 10 and 25 percent brackets, and pay for it all by cutting =
deductions.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">He did not specify how he'd cut dedu=
ctions, and it's basically impossible to see how that could work. The Tax P=
olicy Center found that the new rates, corporate tax reform,
 abolition of estate tax/Obamacare taxes/alternative minimum tax, etc. woul=
d <span style=3D"color:#1F497D">
<a href=3D"http://www.cbpp.org/research/the-ryan-budgets-tax-cuts-nearly-6-=
trillion-in-cost-and-no-plausible-way-to-pay-for-it">cost $5.7 trillion ove=
r 10 years</a></span>. When TPC looked at Mitt Romney's much milder plan in=
 2012, with a top rate of 28 percent
 and a number of in-between brackets, they concluded that there was no way =
to pay for it by
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.taxpolicycenter.org/pub=
lications/distributional-effects-base-broadening-income-tax-reform/full">li=
miting tax deductions that wouldn't wind up costing the middle class or poo=
r money</a></span>. With much more money
 on the line, Ryan has an even greater challenge.<span style=3D"color:#1F49=
7D"><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;color:#1F497D"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">His tax proposals bear a strong rese=
mblance to those of
<span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a href=3D"http://www.vox.com/2015/12/22/1064=
9210/donald-trump-tax-tpc">Donald Trump</a></span>. Trump also wants tax br=
ackets of 10 and 25 percent, plus an additional one of 20. Both would incre=
ase the standard deduction and cut the
 corporate rate. Trump's corporate cut is bigger &#8212; down to a rate of =
15 percent, not 25 as under Ryan's plan &#8212; but unlike Ryan he's never =
proposed eliminating taxes on capital gains and dividends. Ted Cruz has onl=
y a 10 percent flat tax on income, but subjects
 capital gains to it, and borrows Ryan's <span style=3D"color:#1F497D"><a h=
ref=3D"http://www.vox.com/2016/2/16/11019986/ted-cruz-tax-policy-center">id=
ea of turning the corporate tax into a VAT</a></span>.<span style=3D"color:=
#1F497D"><o:p></o:p></span></span></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;;color:#1F497D"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></spa=
n></p>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:12.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ti=
mes New Roman&quot;,&quot;serif&quot;">So despite Ryan's repeated attempts =
to rebrand himself as a moderate, pragmatic leader, his record shows him to=
 be anything but. He's a doctrinaire, down-the-line supply-sider
 who wants massive cuts to safety net and social insurance programs and equ=
ally massive tax cuts for the wealthy. There is very little daylight betwee=
n him, Donald Trump, and Ted Cruz on these issues, and in some cases he's a=
ctually to the
<i>right</i> of Trump. Yes, he's more supportive of immigration reform, and=
 yes, he avoids engaging in the kind of virulent Islamophobia and racism th=
at Trump does. But when it comes to policy nuts and bolts, they're not far =
apart.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
